window.docContents[151].resolve({"/p-adic-and-Adic-Spaces/The-adic-spectrum/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--p-adic-and-Adic-Spaces--The-adic-spectrum--Affinoid-rings-and-rings-of-integral-elements":{"contents":"Let  be a topological ring. A subring  is a ring of integral elements if it\nis open, integrally closed in , and contained in the subring  of power-bounded\nelements. The pair  is then an affinoid ring (or Huber pair). Every ring of integral\nelements automatically contains all topologically nilpotent elements. Following Wedhorn\nDefinition 7.14, Remark 7.15.\nFormalised in Adic-Spaces: IsRingOfIntegralElements, IsAffinoidRing — sorry-free.\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009p-adic and Adic Spaces\u0009The adic spectrum","header":"5.12.1. Affinoid rings and rings of integral elements","id":"/p-adic-and-Adic-Spaces/The-adic-spectrum/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--p-adic-and-Adic-Spaces--The-adic-spectrum--Affinoid-rings-and-rings-of-integral-elements"}});